│ an instruction that it believes does not touch memory.\n\nThe backtrace shows the crash    │
│ happens within `LICM`'s sinking logic (`sink` -> `sinkThroughTriviallyReplaceablePHI` ->   │
│ `cloneInstructionInExitBlock`). The `opt` log confirms that `LICM` is trying to sink the   │
│ instruction `%i3 = call i32 @bar()`.\n\n### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log\n\nThe key components │
│ are:\n- **The Pass Pipeline**: `loop-mssa(simple-loop-unswitch<nontrivial>,licm)`. This    │
│ means `simple-loop-unswitch` runs first, followed by `LICM`.\n- **The Code**: The loop     │
│ contains an indirect call `call i32 %i()`, where `%i` is a `select` between a              │
│ memory-accessing pointer (`%arg1`) and a `memory(none)` function (`@bar`). The branch      │
│ condition `%arg` is loop-invariant.\n- **The Transformation**: `simple-loop-unswitch`      │
│ transforms the loop. It creates two versions of the loop body, one for each path of the    │
│ invariant condition `%arg`.\n  - In the path where `%arg` is false, the `select` is        │
│ resolved to `@bar`, and the indirect call becomes a direct call: `call i32 @bar()`. This   │
│ call is marked `memory(none)`.\n- **The Crash**: `LICM` then analyzes the unswitched loop. │
│ It identifies the `call @bar()` as sinkable. When it tries to sink this instruction, it    │
│ needs to update `MemorySSA`. However, since `call @bar()` has the `memory(none)`           │
│ attribute, `MemorySSA`'s `getMemoryAccess()` returns `nullptr`. This `nullptr` is then     │
│ passed to `createDefinedAccess`, causing the assertion failure.\n\n### 3. Root Cause       │
│ Analysis\n\nThe root cause lies in `LICM`'s sinking logic. The function `sink` in          │
│ `LICM.cpp` attempts to sink instructions out of a loop into its exit blocks. Before doing  │
│ so, it performs several safety checks. However, it fails to check whether the instruction  │
│ it is about to sink actually has a `MemoryAccess` in `MemorySSA`.\n\nThe `sink` function   │
│ calls `sinkThroughTriviallyReplaceablePHI`, which in turn calls                            │
│ `cloneInstructionInExitBlock`. Inside `cloneInstructionInExitBlock`, a new `MemoryAccess`  │
│ is created for the cloned instruction using `MSSA.createMemoryAccessInBB`. This eventually │
│ calls `createDefinedAccess`, which asserts because `getMemoryAccess(I)` for the original   │
│ `call @bar()` instruction returns `nullptr`.\n\nThe fundamental mistake is that `LICM`     │
│ assumes any instruction it tries to sink will have a corresponding `MemoryAccess` if       │
│ `MemorySSA` is available. This assumption is incorrect for instructions that do not access │
│ memory, such as a call to a `memory(none)` function. The `MemorySSA` analysis correctly    │
│ identifies that this call does not access memory and therefore does not create a           │
│ `MemoryAccess` for it. `LICM` should respect this.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe │
│ fix is to prevent `LICM` from attempting to sink instructions that do not have a           │
│ `MemoryAccess` in `MemorySSA`. A simple check in the `sink` function, before any sinking   │
│ logic is invoked, will solve this problem.\n\n```cpp\n//                                   │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/LICM.cpp\n\n// Add this check at the beginning of the sink      │
│ function.\nif (MSSA && !MSSA->getMemoryAccess(&I))\n  return false;\n```\n\nThis ensures   │
│ that if `MemorySSA` is active, we only proceed with sinking if the instruction is          │
│ recognized by `MemorySSA` as a memory-accessing instruction.\n\nHere is the specific edit  │
│ point:\n\n*   **File**: `llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/LICM.cpp`\n*   **Lines**: 1688-1688\n* │
│ **Content**:\n    ```cpp\n    if (MSSA && !MSSA->getMemoryAccess(&I))\n      return        │
│ false;\n    ```\n\nThis should be inserted at the beginning of the `sink` function.\n\n### │
│ 5. Conclusion\n\nThe proposed fix is a guard in `LICM`'s `sink` function. It prevents the  │
│ pass from trying to sink an instruction that `MemorySSA` has determined does not access    │
│ memory. This change is minimal, correct, and directly addresses the root cause of the      │
│ crash without affecting the sinking of legitimate memory-accessing instructions."})        │
